[{"id":31618,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$75 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$300 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$240 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$152 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For BCC, $\\sqrt{3} a=4 r$\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} \\times 351}{4}=152 \\mathrm{~pm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":31559,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Schottky defect decreases the density of the substance.","Frenkel defect does not alter the density of the substance.","Interstitial defect increases the density of the substance.","Vacancy defect increases the density of the substance."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Frenkel Defect: This defect is shown by ionic solids. The smaller ion (usually cation) is dislocated from its normal site to an interstitial site. It creates a vacancy defect at its original site and an interstitial defect at its new location. Frenkel defect is also called dislocation defect. It does not change the density of the solid. In all other defects there is a change in the density.</p><p>In Schottky defect equal number of cation and anion are missing from their position so, it&nbsp;decreases the density of the substance.</p><p>In Interstitial defect extra atoms are present at interstitial position so, it&nbsp;increases the density of the substance.</p><p>Due to vacancy defect density of the substance will decrease. since atoms are missing from their positions.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31610,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Coordination number in bcc mode of packing is 8 .","Coordination number in hep mode of packing is 12 .","Void space in hcp mode of packing is $32 \\%$.","Void space in ccp mode of packing is $26 \\%$."],"answer":2,"solution":"The $h c p$ arrangement of atoms occupies $74 \\%$ of the available space and thus has $26 \\%$ vacant space.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31548,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Bravais Lattice refers to the 14 different 3-dimensional configurations into which atoms can be arranged in crystals. The smallest group of symmetrically aligned atoms which can be repeated in an array to make up the entire crystal is called a unit cell. Crystal systems where body centred unit cell can be found are Cubic, orthorhombic and tetragonal</p><p>Hence, correct answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31575,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MA</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>In HCP unit cell number of effective number of atoms is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>,</p><p>so&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>Number of tetrahedral voids</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;2 x number of&nbsp;atoms forming the lattice&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></msub></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31555,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XY</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The share of the atom present at corner of the cube is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>8</mn></math>. The share of the atom at face centre is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;Hence, the molecule can be represented as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>(Empirical formula)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31627,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["super-cooled liquid","gel","polymeric mixture","micro-crystalline solid"],"answer":0,"solution":"Glass is a transparent or translucent super cooled liquid.","type":"m