ath xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math></p><p>No. of mole <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>No. of molecule <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Frenkel defect","Frenkel and Schottky defects","Interstitial defect","Schottky defect"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":31607,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </msub> </mrow> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mn>3</mn> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </msub> </mrow> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </msub> </mrow> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <msqrt> <mn>3</mn> </msqrt> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>a</mo> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </msub> </mrow> <mo>+</mo> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mn>3</mn> </msqrt> <mtext>a</mtext> </mrow> </math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math> <mtext>8</mtext> </math> chloride ions at <math> <mtext>8</mtext> </math> corners <math> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mtext>Cs</mtext></mrow> <mtext>+</mtext> </msup> </mrow> </math> cation at body centre along body diagonal there will be one <math> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mtext>Cs</mtext></mrow> <mtext>+</mtext> </msup> </mrow> </math> cation and <math> <mrow> <mtext>2</mtext><mtext>&#8196;</mtext><msup> <mrow> <mtext>Cl</mtext></mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> ions at ends of body diagonal.<br /><math> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <mn>2</mn> <msub> <mtext>r</mtext> <msup> <mtext>Cl</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </msub> <mo>=</mo> <msqrt> <mn>3</mn> </msqrt> <mo>a</mo> </mrow> </math><br /><math> <mtext>a</mtext> </math> is edge length<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9bd5c5b8-0e91-499e-be2f-eefe7ff2fb6e-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 191px;\" /><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":31608,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$157 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$128 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$108 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$181 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For FCC,\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4}=\\frac{a}{2 \\sqrt{2}}=0.3535 a$\ngiven $a=361 \\mathrm{~pm}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\nr & =0.3535 \\times 361 \\\\\n& =128 \\mathrm{~pm}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31614,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$174 \\mathrm{pm}$","$158 \\mathrm{pm}$","$142 \\mathrm{pm}$","$126 \\mathrm{pm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For bcc structure\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\text { Interionic distance }= & r^{+}+r^{-}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} a \\\\\n& (a=\\text { edge length })\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& r_{\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}}^{+}+r_{\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}}^{-}=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} a \\\\\n& r_{\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}}^{+}+180=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\times 390\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\mathrm{r}_{\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}}^{+}=338 \\mathrm{pm}-180 \\mathrm{pm}=158 \\mathrm{pm}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31546,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of crystal can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo></math>density of the unit cell</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Effective atomic number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Molar mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math>Avogadro&#39;s number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Edge length of the unit cell</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31593,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;</p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> forms HCP&nbsp;as&nbsp;anions are larger in size.</p><p>From the formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,</p><p>Number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> atoms<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>,</p><p>Then, number of tetrahedral voids&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo></math>Tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;is occupying tetrahedral voids,</p><p>&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br />Therefore, formula of the compound<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31587,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>6</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>SC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></math></p><p>[Atoms are only at the corners]</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;</p><p>[Atoms are at the corners and at the body center]</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>[Atoms are at the corners and at the face centers]</p><p>Here,&nbsp;Z=&nbsp;effective number of atoms in the unit cell.</p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>SC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><mo>&#8203;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/355fb20b-1fd9-4fda-a088-cbe666e07245-image15.png\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/374cb6e0-20e0-4cf2-8131-dab7a3574466-image16.png\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16c8d674-da79-4a5c-b202-6707fa0b21ca-image17.png\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>SC</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>BCC</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>FCC</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31590,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For ccp structure: <br/>Number of octahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>  <br/>Number of tetrahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (number of atoms present in ccp structure) <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/>So formula is <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\frac{20}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{24}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{12}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} V & =n \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =4 \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":31571,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Carbon atoms occupy FCC lattice points as well as half of the tetrahedral voids</p><p>therefore number of carbon atoms atoms per unit cell <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31572,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is false","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct<br />explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>.</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is true.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>."],"answer":1,"solution":"Sharp glass edges are heated to make them smooth. Because on heating glass melts and the surface of the liquid tends to take the rounded shape at the edges which has minimum surface area. This is called fire polishing of glass. Correct explanation for this is surface tension.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31561,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given: Molar mass of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>AB</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Atomicwt</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Atomicwt</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> atomic wt. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is 2 times of atomic wt. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> Integer answer is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31566,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Antiferromagnetism, type of magnetism in solids&nbsp;in which adjacent ions that behave as tiny magnets</p><p>Paramagnetism&nbsp;is a form of magnetism whereby some materials are weakly attracted by an externally applied magnetic field, and form internal, induced magnetic fields in the direction of the applied magnetic field.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MnO</mi></math>- Antiferromagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>- Paramagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>- Diamagnetism<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>- Ferrimagnetism</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31613,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Density of crystals remains unaffected due to Frenkel defect.","In BCC unit cell the void space is $32 \\%$.","Density of crystals decreases due to Schottky defect.","Electrical conductivity of semiconductors and metals increases with increase in temperature."],"answer":3,"solution":"The electrical resistance of metals depends upon temperature. Electrical resistance decreases with decrease in temperature and becomes zero near the absolute temperature. Material in this state is said to possess super conductivity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31617,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$314.20 \\mathrm{pm}$","$1.41 \\mathrm{pm}$","$200 \\mathrm{pm}$","$216 \\mathrm{pm}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"For bcc structure\n$$\nd=\\frac{\\sqrt{3} a}{2}\n$$\nwhere $d=$ distance between two atoms $a=$ edge length\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 1.73=\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} a \\\\\n& a=\\frac{2 \\times 1.73}{\\sqrt{3}}=2 Å=200 \\mathrm{pm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31553,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of the crystal can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>density</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>effective</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atoms</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>Avogadro</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Edge</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>length</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>72</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31573,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MgO</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Mn</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> shows magnetic properties.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31621,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$30 \\%$ and $26 \\%$","$26 \\%$ and $32 \\%$","$32 \\%$ and $48 \\%$","$48 \\%$ and $26 \\%$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Packing fraction of cubic close packing and body centred packing are $0.74$ and $0.68$ respectively.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{A}\\mathrm{~B}$","$\\mathrm{A}_2 \\mathrm{~B}$","$\\mathrm{A}\\mathrm{~B}_3$","$\\mathrm{A}_3 \\mathrm{~B}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\nA=\\frac{1}{8} \\times 8=1\n$$\n(Corner)\n$\\mathrm{B}=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 6=3$\n(Face centre)\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{AB}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":31569,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Hexagonal","Orthorhombic","Monoclinic","Triclinic"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#947;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>&#8800;</mo><mi>&#946;</mi></math>&nbsp;are parameters of monoclinic unit cell.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31558,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is body centred cubic, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>Let mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;atom of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Edge length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mi>pm</mi></math></p><p>Density&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org